metadata.name: fx(mash) #347
metadata.description:
fx(mash) is my humble contribution to celebrating #fxhashturnsone

This series is based on a simple algorithm - lines of a random length are drawn on a square grid until the grid is full.

I have added a variety of features based on some of my favorite fxhash projects and a few special guests.

This collection is intentionally diverse and disorderly, that's a nice way of saying I only had a short period of time following the release of Acequia. As a result, some of the outputs might be weird, messy, or even bordering on broken (if you get one of the latter please let me know and I'll reimburse you).

Despite being a bit rough around the edges, I hope fx(mash) reflects some measure of my love for the fxhash community. If you're feeling kind, then perhaps it even harks back to the experimental early days :)

The last year has been an incredible journey, thank you for letting me be a part of our story so far.

Controls (in live view):

- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [g] to toggle grain
- Press [h] for a high-res output

Beta Controls (in live view, definitely not fully tested):

- Press [p] to start/pause animation
- Press [i] to slow down animation
- Press [o] to speed up animation

All primary sales go to Savepakistan.


Acknowledgements:

fx(mash) uses Gorilla Sun's grain implementation, a big thanks to him and meezwhite for a great article that is well worth supporting https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/all-about-that-grain

metadata.name: Modulation #188
metadata.description:
Isometric cityscapes, patterns and geometries generated by trigonometric functions and rendered as SVG.

The SVG can be saved by pressing "s" on the full-screen view.
A PNG version can be exported by pressing "e" on the full-screen view.

By default the dimensions of the export are 6000×7500.
These dimensions can be changed by adding, for example, ?w=12000 to the full-screen page URL, where w is the desired width. Then press "e" to export at this size.

metadata.name: WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition #109
metadata.description:
WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition is our official collaboration with Jeres, who was kind enough to work with us in support of the show. The project leans into classic Olympic poster design motifs, embellished by Jeres' signature approach to color and shape. Huge thanks to Jeres for donating their time and enthusiasm to this one, we hope you enjoy it!

As with all WTBS projects, your minting will directly support the podcast and keep us going (and more importantly, collecting!). Our goal is to keep the show free from ads and fully supported by the community, your donations and contributions continue to make that possible. Thank you in advance to everyone who chooses to mint!

Jeres: I love vintage posters. When going to second-hand shops, flea markets or wherever people are selling their used goods, I’m always on the lookout for what people used to hang on their walls. Bauhaus-inspired posters, socialist propaganda, Nagel prints, anything art deco, etc.. but whenever I come across something Olympics inspired I always feel like I hit pay dirt. There’s something about the clean, simple design being used to show people coming together along with the undertones of human excellence that just feels special. And circles. I love circles. I hope you enjoy this collection as much as I enjoyed putting it together with Trinity and Will.

Approximate rarity notes:
5%: Gold Edition
10%: Silver Edition
15%: Bronze Edition 

Commands in fullscreen mode:
S : Save current resolution
1 : Save 2000x3000px
2 : Save 4000x6000px
3 : Save 6000x9000px
4 : Save 8000x12000px
5 : Save 10000x15000px

(The higher the resolution, the longer it takes to render/save. use Chrome for best results.)

metadata.name: Gammalt #331
metadata.description:
Celebrating getting old with Fx(hash).

Save as png:
Click “s”
or double click/tap

Resolution:
Default image width = 2000px and aspect ratio = 4:3.
Modify the image width between 2000px and 10000px by adding “&w=xxxx” to the url (e.g. &w=4000).
High resolutions are computationally expensive and may take a while.

Background:
The canvas background texture is visible by default. This can be toggled off by adding “&b=0” to the url.
The background scales with resolution to mimic a bigger canvas so it will look different at different resolutions.
At high resolutions a Moiré pattern may appear on the canvas background texture due to the way images are resized in the browser. It’s always recommended to download a full resolution version of the piece.

By KRANKARTA
Created on Firefox desktop 105.0 on 2022-11-11 in javascript and GLSL.
CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: Hillhouse #49
metadata.description:
On every important holiday of my childhood, I would return to my hometown, a village in a hilly area. The mist in the morning would have a psychedelic texture, like water ripples under the smudge of the deep blue sky. But at sunrise, the atmosphere becomes lively. All year round, spring, summer, autumn and winter, colourful and dreamlike.

The buildings in my hometown are white walls and black tiles. The fog in the village is very close to the ground, and the terrain is relatively undulating. I can often see rows of angular eaves and white walls penetrating the fog on other hillsides, like houses standing in the clouds. At that time, I always liked to climb up the hillside under the sunset after dinner, looking down at the village surrounded by clouds and mist after the rain. I could always stay at the top of the mountain and watch the clouds change from orange-red to blue. I didn't leave until the sky turned completely black. After I left the village, whenever I described such a scene with my friends, I would call such a building: Hillhouse.

I'm not in China now, and I don't know when I'll be able to see the misty landscape of my hometown again to create Hillhouse, a memorial to the village that inspired my aesthetics during my childhood.

I noticed many of my friends said after seeing my works that my townhouse is like a mountain. My original idea was to appropriately enlarge the proportion of the roof in the picture because I tried to balance the natural landscape and humanistic value in the work. Moreover, I also deliberately strengthened the corners and some obvious small pavilion buildings to make it different from the mountains. But, of course, art depends on personal understanding, so that's fine.


Mint at 188 tez, I will provide a 1/1 customised video NFT, physical printed work, and one WL spot for my following 2 projects on fxhash. You can choose your favourite palette and mountain style in our UI system and the soundtrack first. Then I will create a 20-sec video version NFT for you. The sound is originally created by @Dreminor. 

In terms of printed work, it will be printed on museum quality acid-free paper by giclee print technique. It will never fade 100 yrs. And the printed work will have my signature and seal on it. So yes I will give it to you with no charge, except the delivery fee requested from the delivery company.

I also considered secondary market transactions for collectors who minted at 188. I will offer a NEW customized video NFT and a NEW printed work to collectors who purchase the token minted in 188tez for more than 188tez on the secondary market. The video NFT is free but I will charge 100tez for the new printed work.

Mint at 138 tez, I will provide a printed work and one WL spot for my next project on fxhash.

Mint at 64 tez. I will provide one WL spot for my next project on fxhash.


Btw, the computational expense in this project is high, so if you cannot open live, please try to use a better computer to generate or use Visual Studio Code. If you cannot solve this problem, feel free to contact me, I would like to offer help.

Due to some reasons, the preview will be different from the generative artwork. So pls open live to have a look and it will be much better than preview.

This project is created by Arctic--Cc and Van.

metadata.name: Ceremony #342
metadata.description:
This series celebrates fxhash turning one. #fxhashturnsone

I’m so grateful for this place and have ho idea how to adequately articulate how much this platform has changed my life, but it has. A million thanks to the team. You are so appreciated as are the artists and collectors that have made this such a beautiful community. 🥂

Definitely check out “Forever” mode by tapping “F” or mouse click/tap — it will animate (you guessed it) forever and will change its layout every 365 frames, in honor of this wonderful year, and every year after. Some forever modes will “never forget” and others will fade as they progress. No idea if that’s a metaphor but it is a trait, that much I know.

All primary sales are donated to Code/Art, which is a charity that uses “…Art to Inspire Girls in Computer Science.” Read about Code/Art here: https://www.code-art.com/

Ceremony uses public domain art (which is the original, more implicit version CC0) made exclusively by women.

See fxtext article linked from the project page for a gallery of the source material and other notes.

Ceremony is also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

F : “Forever” mode (tap after initial render completes)
P : Pause/Play
(mouse click/tap also works to start “Forever” mode or Pause/Play)

A : Add Grain (only works when paused in “Forever” mode.)
G : Toggle Grain (resets the whole piece)
M : Toggle Matte (resets the whole piece)

S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density (resets the whole piece)
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

If you want to start in "Forever" mode, you can append "&forever=true" to the url in the live view.
You can also add pixel density to the url by appending “&density=2” (or 3, 4, etc) to have it render at higher resolutions by default.

metadata.name: Fragment of Time #237
metadata.description:
"Year" is a mere four-letter word. But in reality, much has occurred. There are 12 months or approximately 365 days in a year. I joined fxhash about 4 months ago. And a lot has happened in my life since then. Can you imagine what happened to the people who founded, participated in, and maintained fxhash from its founding days? Everyday must've been different, and each day has its own pattern and color.

I've felt as if I lived in two different worlds since joining fxhash. I'm an architect by day, and a creator by night. I'm a part of fxhash, and I believe every single one of us experiences it that way. Each day has its own pattern and color.

This piece is my way of imagining what this community has gone through in a year. Each block represents a month from November 2021 to October 2022, with every block consists of smaller blocks that represents a day. Each of these days have their own colors and patterns. Every day tells its own story. But when you imagine a bigger picture of what happened in a year, you will see a specific pattern and color that you can keep as one big composition, and that gives you a year full of stories to admire.

I try to participate in the anniversary event as a way of expressing my gratitude. For everyone who has helped build this community so vibrant and meaningful - you have created such a world, and subsequently made my year. And therefore to me, you are all wonderful souls. So many artists, collectors, coders, art enthusiasts, and all of fxhash's teams have inspired me. Don't stop creating awesome stuff. Happy Birthday fxhash!!

metadata.name: fx(splash) #291
metadata.description:
To celebrate fx(hash) turning 1 year old I've created this token as a part of the #fxhashturnsone event! It's a playful and colorful token symbolizing the experiences I've had with this platform.


The piece uses shaders to generate it's visuals which means that outputs will vary from device to device, and the preview might not look the exact same as your live view.

For that same reason I do not recommend running this piece on a mobile device as the shaders can be quite heavy and blurry on lower-tier hardware. My recommended way of viewing this token is on a pc.


--

To open the export menu double click the screen. Here you can export in a multitude of resolutions.

--


50% of primary proceeds will be donated to the processing foundation, learn more about them here:
https://processingfoundation.org

Made with opengl shaders and p5js by WootScoot, 2022.
